I've created a corrected version with two better approaches to place the tables side by side with top alignment and an equation under the right table:

### Method 1: Using Saveboxes for Precise Positioning

The first approach uses LaTeX saveboxes to measure the exact dimensions:

1. We measure both tables in advance:
   ```latex
   \newsavebox{\lefttablebox}
   \newsavebox{\righttablebox}
   \sbox{\lefttablebox}{...} % Store the left table
   \sbox{\righttablebox}{...} % Store the right table
   ```

2. We calculate the height difference to know how much space we have for equations:
   ```latex
   \newlength{\tableheightdiff}
   \setlength{\tableheightdiff}{\ht\lefttablebox}
   \addtolength{\tableheightdiff}{-\ht\righttablebox}
   \addtolength{\tableheightdiff}{-1.5cm} % Subtract caption height
   ```

3. Then we place them side by side with proper alignment:
   ```latex
   \begin{minipage}[t]{0.48\textwidth}
       \centering
       \usebox{\lefttablebox}
       \caption{$\mathbf{R}_7$ Multiplication Table}
   \end{minipage}%
   \hfill
   \begin{minipage}[t]{0.48\textwidth}
       \centering
       \usebox{\righttablebox}
       \caption{$\mathbf{R}_3$ Multiplication Table}

       \vspace{0.5cm} % Add a little gap
       \begin{align}
           \mathbf{x} \times \mathbf{y} &= \mathbf{z} \\
           % Equations here
       \end{align}
   \end{minipage}
   ```

This approach ensures that both tables are properly aligned at the top, and you have precise control over the equation placement.

### Method 2: Everything in a Single TikZ Picture

The second method puts everything into a single TikZ picture:

```latex
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
    % Left table (R7)
    \node[htaucell] at (0, 0) {$\mathbf{\times}$};
    % Rest of left table...

    % Caption for left table
    \node[align=center, below] at (3.5, -7.5) {$\mathbf{R}_7$ Multiplication Table};

    % Right table (R3), positioned to the right
    \begin{scope}[xshift=10cm]
        \node[hzerocell] at (0, 0) {$\mathbf{\times}$};
        % Rest of right table...

        % Caption for right table
        \node[align=center, below] at (1.5, -4) {$\mathbf{R}_3$ Multiplication Table};

        % Equation below the right table
        \node[align=center] at (1.5, -6) {$\mathbf{x} \times \mathbf{y} = \mathbf{z}$};
        \node[align=center] at (1.5, -6.7) {$\mathbf{y} \times \mathbf{z} = \mathbf{x}$};
        \node[align=center] at (1.5, -7.4) {$\mathbf{z} \times \mathbf{x} = \mathbf{y}$};
    \end{scope}
\end{tikzpicture}
```

This gives you complete control over the placement of all elements. The tables automatically align at the top, and you can position the equations exactly where you want them. The captions are also included directly in the TikZ picture.

The first method is more "LaTeX-like" and integrates better with LaTeX's figure numbering and referencing. The second method gives you more direct control over the visual layout but requires you to handle the captions manually.

