 To create a macro that dynamically changes based on another variable's value, you need to use TeX's capability to expand macros. Here's how to define the macro you're looking for:

```latex
\def\e0unit{\hat{\csname e0\endcsname}}
```

Then you can define `\e0` and use `\e0unit` as follows:

```latex
\def\e0{\tau}
\e0unit % This will produce \hat{\tau}

\def\e0{x}
\e0unit % This will now produce \hat{x}
```

A full example would be:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\def\e0unit{\hat{\csname e0\endcsname}}

\begin{document}

\def\e0{\tau}
$\e0unit$ % Produces \hat{\tau}

\def\e0{x}
$\e0unit$ % Produces \hat{x}

\def\e0{y}
$\e0unit$ % Produces \hat{y}

\end{document}
```

If you need to use this in math mode consistently, you could also define it as:

```latex
\def\e0unit{\hat{\csname e0\endcsname}}
```

This uses the `\csname...\endcsname` construct which dynamically creates a command name from its contents. When TeX sees `\csname e0\endcsname`, it creates the token `\e0` and then expands it.

For more complex cases with values passed as arguments, you might use:

```latex
\newcommand{\unitvector}[1]{\hat{\csname e#1\endcsname}}
```

Then you can use:
```latex
\def\e0{\tau}
\def\e1{x}
\def\e2{y}

$\unitvector{0}$ % Produces \hat{\tau}
$\unitvector{1}$ % Produces \hat{x}
$\unitvector{2}$ % Produces \hat{y}
```

This gives you a flexible system for creating dynamic macros that adapt based on the values of other macros.

