 The issue is that your definition is treating `e1` as a literal string rather than expanding it as a macro. Let me show you how to fix it.

Your current definition:
```latex
\def\e1unit{\hat{e1}}
```

This creates a macro `\e1unit` that will always produce `\hat{e1}`. It doesn't know that you want it to use the value of `\e1`.

Instead, you need to use TeX's expansion mechanism. Here are two working solutions:

### Solution 1: Using `\csname`

```latex
\def\e1unit{\hat{\csname e1\endcsname}}
```

This uses TeX's `\csname...\endcsname` construct which creates a control sequence named `e1` and then expands it.

### Solution 2: Using a more explicit expansion

```latex
\def\e1unit{\expandafter\hat\expandafter{\e1}}
```

This uses `\expandafter` to expand `\e1` before `\hat` is applied to it.

### Complete working example

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

% Define the base variable
\def\e1{\tau}

% Method 1: Using csname
\def\e1unitA{\hat{\csname e1\endcsname}}

% Method 2: Using expandafter
\def\e1unitB{\expandafter\hat\expandafter{\e1}}

\begin{document}

Using csname: $\e1unitA$ % This will produce \hat{\tau}

Using expandafter: $\e1unitB$ % This will also produce \hat{\tau}

% Let's change the value and see it update
\def\e1{x}

Now with new value:
$\e1unitA$, $\e1unitB$ % Both produce \hat{x}

\end{document}
```

The most robust approach is probably the first one with `\csname`. It correctly handles the case if `\e1` might not be defined.

